   `uint32_t` count by the size of the `Record` struct, causing an overflow for
   large counts. This results in an undersized allocation, leading to a heap-
   buffer-overflow when writing to the buffer.
   
   [LOCAL FIX:] To fix the immediate symptom, change the multiplication to use a
   larger integer type, such as `uint64_t`, to prevent the overflow. Replace
   `Record *rs = make_records(n);` with `Record *rs =
   make_records((uint64_t)n);`.
   
   [GLOBAL FIX:] To prevent this class of bug, consider changing the
   `make_records` function to use a compile-time check to ensure that the count
   can fit in the allocated memory. Alternatively, redesign the function to use
   a dynamically-sized allocation, such as `std::vector<Record>`, which can
   handle large counts without overflowing.
